        <h4>What is Finite Automata?</h4>
        <p>A Finite Automaton (FA) is a simple abstract machine used to recognize patterns and process input strings, forming the mathematical foundation for regular languages and many applications in computer science. It consists of a finite number of states and transitions between them, based on input symbols. If the machine ends in an accepting (final) state after reading the input, the input is accepted; otherwise, it is rejected.</p>
        <h4 class="mt-4">Real-World Applications</h4>
        <ul>
            <li><b>Lexical Analysis in Compilers:</b> Tokenizing source code into keywords, operators, and identifiers.</li>
            <li><b>Pattern Recognition:</b> Searching and matching patterns in text (e.g., regular expressions).</li>
            <li><b>Digital Circuit Design:</b> Modeling sequential circuits like traffic lights, elevators, and vending machines.</li>
            <li><b>Text Editors & Spell Checkers:</b> Finding/replacing patterns and checking word validity.</li>
            <li><b>Network Protocols:</b> Modeling connection states (e.g., TCP SYN, ACK, FIN).</li>
            <li><b>Decision Automation:</b> Automating processes like traffic light controllers.</li>
        </ul>
        <h4 class="mt-4">Key Features of Finite Automata</h4>
        <ul>
            <li><b>Input:</b> Sequence of symbols (from an alphabet, e.g., {a, b}).</li>
            <li><b>States:</b> Different configurations the machine can be in.</li>
            <li><b>Transitions:</b> Rules for moving from one state to another based on input.</li>
            <li><b>Output:</b> Accept or reject the input string.</li>
        </ul>
        <h4 class="mt-4">Formal Definition (5-Tuple)</h4>
        <div class="alert alert-info mt-2 p-3 rounded">
            <p>A finite automaton is defined as:</p>
            <pre><code class="language-mermaid">M = (Q, Σ, δ, q₀, F)</code></pre>
            <p>Where:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><b>Q:</b> Finite set of states</li>
                <li><b>Σ:</b> Finite set of input symbols (alphabet)</li>
                <li><b>δ:</b> Transition function (Q × Σ → Q for DFA, Q × Σ → 2<sup>Q</sup> for NFA)</li>
                <li><b>q₀:</b> Initial/start state (q₀ ∈ Q)</li>
                <li><b>F:</b> Set of final/accepting states (F ⊆ Q)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <h4 class="mt-4">Types of Finite Automata</h4>
        <h6>1. Deterministic Finite Automaton (DFA)</h6>
        <ul>
            <li>For each state and input symbol, there is exactly one transition.</li>
            <li>No empty (epsilon) transitions.</li>
            <li>Always predictable: one path for each input string.</li>
        </ul>
