            <h6>How it works:</h6>
            <ul>
                <li>On reading 'a', NFA can stay in q₀ or move to q₁.</li>
                <li>If any path ends in q₁ after reading the input, the string is accepted.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <h4 class="mt-4">DFA vs. NFA: Key Differences</h4>
        <div class="table-responsive bg-dark p-2 rounded">
            <table class="table table-bordered table-sm text-white">
                <thead class="table-light">
                    <tr><th>Feature</th><th>DFA</th><th>NFA</th></tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <tr><td>Transitions</td><td>Exactly one per symbol per state</td><td>Zero, one, or many per symbol</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>Epsilon (ε) transitions</td><td>Not allowed</td><td>Allowed</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>Acceptance</td><td>Unique path</td><td>Multiple possible paths</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>Construction</td><td>More difficult, more states</td><td>Easier, fewer states</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>Efficiency</td><td>Faster, less backtracking</td><td>May require backtracking</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>Power</td><td>Both recognize regular languages</td><td>Both recognize regular languages</td></tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </div>
        <p><b>Note:</b> Every NFA can be converted to an equivalent DFA, though the DFA may have more states.</p>
        <h4 class="mt-4">How Finite Automata Work: Step-by-Step</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Start at the initial state.</li>
            <li>Read the input string one symbol at a time.</li>
            <li>Follow transitions according to the transition function.</li>
            <li>If, after reading the whole string, the automaton is in a final state, the string is accepted. Otherwise, it is rejected.</li>
        </ul>
